  "prompt": "What are the chances of the electoral college changing vote for Clinton?",
  "response": "The chances of the Electoral College changing its vote for Hillary Clinton are extremely low. In the United States, the Electoral College casts the official votes for president following the general election. Electors are typically pledged to vote for the candidate who won the popular vote in their state, and most states have laws binding them to this pledge. While there have been instances of \"faithless electors\" who did not vote according to their pledge, these cases are rare and have never changed the outcome of an election.\n\nMoreover, once an election is certified and the winner is inaugurated, the results are considered final. Hillary Clinton ran for president in 2016 and lost to Donald Trump, who was inaugurated in January 2017. Therefore, there is no mechanism or precedent for the Electoral College to retroactively change its vote for a past election.",
